<!-- By Dependent Issues (Action) - DO NOT REMOVE -->

I don't quite like how the following square is looking:
`Implies`/`Imp` | `Language.Theory.Implies`
`Iff` | `Language.Theory.SemanticallyEquivalent`

What do you think of renaming the right column so that it looks more consistent? Here are a few suggestions (all in the `Language.Theory` namespace):
* `SemanticallyImplies`, `SemanticallyEquivalent`
* `SemanticImp`, `SemanticIff`
* `Imp`, `Iff`

I agree that making these match makes sense - I think it should be down to the last two options, so the question is just whether to specify `Semantic`. The reason for doing this is because I hope that at some point, it would be good to have a first-order proof system, and in that case, there's a distinction between a theory modelling an implication/equivalence and the theory proving it. These turn out to be the same, of course, because of the completeness theorem, so it's just a question of which should be the _definition_ of `Theory.Imp` and `Theory.Iff`. At the moment, I'd say I over-futureproofed `SemanticallyEquivalent`, so probably this should just be `Imp` and `Iff`.
I'll let you make the final call. It's easy enough to rename the predicate later (and probably we won't need deprecations since you are currently the sole downstream user of this material)
I've finally gone and used the simplest possible choice on the names. Hopefully I've capitalized (or uncapitalized) the names of lemmas appropriately.

```suggestion
    Ï† â‡”[T] Ïˆ â†” Ï† âŸ¹[T] Ïˆ âˆ§ Ïˆ âŸ¹[T] Ï† := by
```
parses as expected?
I've just tried a range of precedences, and nothing seemed to work. Do you have a suggestion of something to change other than the number `25`?
I'll try playing with precedences

Half serious, but that could be
```suggestion
protected theorem mp {Ï† Ïˆ : L.BoundedFormula Î± n} (h : Ï† â‡”[T] Ïˆ) :
    Ï† âŸ¹[T] Ïˆ := (semanticallyEquivalent_iff_implies_and_implies.1 h).1
```
then you could also have `mpr`

I'd prefer to name this `sup_imp_left` in analogy with `sup_le_left` for orders
(and similar below)

oops lol

```suggestion

  simp only [BoundedFormula.realize_imp,
    BoundedFormula.realize_top, BoundedFormula.realize_sup, BoundedFormula.realize_not,

```

